msItem.explicit:
Vndarligt þykki mer ær þer uæfit sva
ordskurd um þetta mal ok eroð er
msItem.filiation: Transcript of Jöfraskinna which went missing during the Copenhagen Fire of 1728.
msItem.bibl: Finnur Jónsson, Heimskringla: Nóregs konunga sögur af Snorri Sturluson Var. AM 37 fol.
Schöning, Heimskringla edr Noregs konunga sǫgur af Snorra Sturlusyni Ed. C

supportDesc.foliation: Foliated 1-181 + 99 bis by Kristian Kålund in red ink in the upper right-hand corners .
supportDesc.condition: Due to exposure to humidity especially the last part of the manuscript is stained and brittle; the upper part of f. 181 is missing.

handDesc.handNote: Fols 1-11 are written by Ásgeir Jónsson
The rest of the manuscript is written by a principal in Oslo called Jens Nilssøn.

decoDesc.decoNote: Several of the initials are very large, lavishly ornamented and adorned with dates and information stating the name of the scribe together with the time and the place the transcription was made.

physDesc.additions: The first eleven leaves, containing the prologue and the first part of Ynglinga saga, were added later.

binding.p: The manuscript is full-bound (parchment-bound). Árni Magnússon wrote the title on the spine. Size of binding: 298 212 43

accMat.p: Árni Magnússon tells on two inserted slips: Þessa bök hefi eg fenged af Domino Christiano Wormio 1709 and Þetta epterfylgjande er ritad epter codice Academio, þeim er eg liet setia hryggenn ä, og hefur hann þä heille vered enn hann er nu. patet ex Collatione [Codex Academico = Jöfraskinna]

origin.p: The main part of the manuscript is written in 1567-68 by Jens Nilssøn, headmaster in Oslo. The initial on fol. 103 informs about the origin of this part: Ritad a Rindini i Snikivdalsokn þan. XXI Maij ar. 1567 (written inside the stem of the Þ).
The first eleven leaves are written c. 1688–1707 by Ásgeir Jónsson.

history.acquisition: According to one of the AM-slips Árni Magnússon acquired the manuscript from Christian Worm
